AGI -&nbsp; The ancient Greek site of Anthedon in Gaza was bombed, its "Palace of Napoleon" destroyed and the only private museum burned: the war has put hard evidence of the rich cultural heritage of the Palestinian territory. But for a strange joke of fate, some of its greatest historical treasures are safe in a warehouse in Switzerland. And, absurdly, it is all about the blockade that has made life in the Gaza Strip so difficult in the last 16 years.
&nbsp;
Based on satellite images, the United Nations cultural organization estimates that about 41 historical sites have been damaged since Israel began bombing in response to the Hamas terrorist attack. On the spot, the Palestinian archaeologist Fadel al-Otol > keeps the destruction in real time under control. When it has electricity and Internet access, photos are poured into a WhatsApp group that has created with about 40 young peers mobilized to watch over the wide range of ancient sites and monuments of the territory. As a teenager, in the 1990s, Otol was hired by European archaeological missions before continuing his studies in Switzerland and the Louvre Museum in Paris.
&nbsp;
"All the archaeological remains in the north were affected," told AFP on the phone from Gaza. "Blakhiya (the ancient Greek city of Anthedon>) was bombed directly. There's a huge hole," Otol said. The 13th-century Al-Basha Palace, in the historic center of Gaza City, "was completely destroyed. There were bombings and (then) was razed to the ground. "It contained hundreds of ancient objects and magnificent sarcophagi," added Otol sharing the recent photos of the ruins.
<div </div
It is said that Napoleon had established himself in the stone building ocher at the disastrous end of his Egyptian campaign in 1799. The room where the French emperor allegedly slept was full of Byzantine artifacts. "Our best findings were exhibited in Basha," said AFP Jean-Baptiste Humbert> of the French Biblical and Archaeological School of Jerusalem (EBAF). The tension climbed when the Israeli Antiquities Director, Eli Escusido, published an Instagram video showing Israeli soldiers surrounded by ancient pots and ceramics in the EBAF warehouse in Gaza City. The Palestinians immediately accused the plundering army. But the EBAF archaeologist Rene Elter said he had not seen any evidence of "state looting". "My colleagues managed to get back to the place. The soldiers opened the boxes. We don't know if they took anything," he told AFP.&nbsp; Archaeology is a highly political issue > in Israel and the Palestinian territories, with discoveries often used to justify the claims of the two peoples at war.
&nbsp;
The only natural port repaired between Sinai and Lebanon, Gaza has for centuries been a crossroads of civilization. Point of snout between Africa and Asia and the snout of the incense trade, was covered by Egyptians, Persians, Greeks, Romans and Ottomans. A key figure in the excavation of this glorious past in recent decades has been Jawdat Khoudary, a building and collector of Gaza.
&nbsp;
Gaza, with its "immobili fronte mare", lived a real estate boom in the 1990s after the Oslo peace agreements and the creation of the Palestinian Authority. When the workers dug the ground, they came across many ancient objects. Khoudary has accumulated a treasure of artefacts that opened to foreign archaeologists. Marc-Andre' Haldimann, then curator of the MAH, the art and history museum of Geneva, could not believe in his eyes when he was invited to take a look at the garden of the villa of Khoudary in 2004. "We were faced with 4,000 objects, including a Byzantine column avenue," said AFP.&nbsp; Soon it took shape the idea of organizing a large exhibition to highlight the past of Gaza at the MAH, and then to build a museum in the territory itself so that the Palestinians could appropriate their heritage.
&nbsp;

