AGI - The knife attack in a church in Sydney, Australia, where four people were injured is a "terrorist act", concluded the police, who arrested a 16-year-old boy. A bishop and the young suspect are among the people treated for "non-lethal" > after the attack on Monday evening during a sermon broadcast live in an Assyrian church of the city.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The attack triggered fury among the faithful and clashes in the street. A bishop and the suspect of 16 years, arrested, are treated for "non-gravious injuries". The young black dress approached the altar, raised the right arm and struck with a knife the bishop of the Assyrian community Mar Mari Emmanuel, causing panic and screams among the faithful, as they showed images of the religious function broadcast live stream.&nbsp;> The priest of this branch of Eastern Christians, stabbed at the head and chest, is in stable conditions, informed the Church on Tuesday.
&nbsp;
"After considering all the elements, I said it was an act of terrorism," announced New South Wales police chief Karen Webb, at a press conference. It is considered an act of "religious extremism", > he added, specifying that the suspect is "known to the police" but does not appear in any anti-terrorism file.
&nbsp;
"At this stage it seems to be an individual act," said Mike Burgess, head of Australian intelligence. "There is no indication that someone else is involved, but the investigation remains open," he added, stating that there is no need to increase the level of terrorist threat > in the country.<br> Suspect is in care for wounds to the hand and was taken to a safe place while the attack triggered the fury among the faithful.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Other three people reported minor injuries in the attack and about 30 others were cured because they were wounded in the brawl outside the church. For three hours more than 500 protesters collided with the riot police who wanted to prevent them from entering church and lynching the teenager. Twenty police vehicles and some houses were damaged by protesters who launched bottles, bricks and other objects. AFP has identified the video site as the church of Christ Good Shepherd in Wakeley, a western suburb of Sydney. The neighborhood is known to welcome members of the small Assyrian Christian community who fled persecution and war in Iraq and Syria.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br In the evening it finally returned calm, but in the area other police officers were deployed to protect religious buildings. The head of the government of New South Wales, Chris Minns, appealed to calm in a joint statement to the Christian and Muslim authorities. "We invite everyone to act calmly and respectfully for others," they wrote.
"This is the time to prove that we are strong and united." This new attack arrives two days after another stabbing in Sydney that caused the death of six people, including five women, Saturday in a shopping mall. The terrorist motive for the murder committed by a man suffering from a mental illness that was killed by a policeman was excluded.
